{"title_page": "Muhamad Radhi Mat Din", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2008}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Radhi Mat Din\n|image =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[Image:Radhi.jpg]] -->\n|fullname = Muhamad Radhi bin Mat Din\n|height =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1965|7|17}}\n|birth_place = [[Pokok Sena]], [[Kedah]], [[Malaysia]]\n|currentclub = [[Kedah FA]] (Assistant Coach)\n|clubnumber =\n|position = [[Midfielder]] \n|youthyears1=\n|youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1986\u20131992 | years2 =1986\u20132000\n| clubs1 = Kedah PKNK | clubs2 =[[Kedah FA]]\n| caps1 = ? | goals1 = ? | caps2 = ? | goals2 = ?\n|nationalyears1= 1989\u20131993\n|nationalteam1= [[Malaysia national football team|Malaysia]]\n|nationalcaps1= ? | nationalgoals1 = ?\n|pcupdate =\n|ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Muhamad Radhi bin Mat Din''' (born 17 July 1965) is a [[Malaysia]]n football coach, former [[Association football|footballer]], and politician.\n\n==Football career==\n\nHe spent his entire career by playing in midfield for [[Kedah FA]], where he was also the longest serving captain in club history starting from 1991 to 2000. Radhi made his debut in 1986 and cemented his place in the first team in the 1987 season, succeeding [[Lee Kin Hong]] as Kedah team captain in 1991.\n\nRadhi was an integral part in the golden era of the [[Darul Aman Stadium|Darul Aman]] based club during the 1980s and 1990s where Kedah reached the [[Malaysia Cup]] final matches for seven times from 1987 to 1993. He collected two Malaysia Cup winners medal in 1990 and 1993; [[Malaysia Super League|Division 1]] title in 1993; and [[Malaysia FA Cup|FA Cup]] in 1996. After Kedah won the League and FA Cup championship in 1993, Radhi was honoured with the Malaysian Best Player.\n\nRadhi had a good goal-scoring record, tackle, corner-kick taker and pass well. He represented [[Malaysia national football team|Malaysia]] for about four years from 1989 to 1993. Radhi also known by the nickname \"Captain Marvel\" among Kedah fans during his playing careers with his similar characters of former [[England|English]] footballer [[Bryan Robson]].\n\nAfter his playing career ended, he was employed by Kedah, serving as their second tactician behind [[Mohd Azraai Khor Abdullah]] alongside his former teammate and Kedah legendary [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Ahmad Sabri Ismail]] which three of them generated Kedah to clinched the double treble titles in 2006/07 and 2007/08 M.League seasons.\n\nRadhi played for the [[Malaysia national football team]] at the [[1989 Southeast Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|author=Courtney, Barrie|title=International Matches 1989 - Asisa|url=http://www.rsssf.com/intldetails/1989as.html|date=2 February 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nOn 14 April 2018, Radhi was announced as a candidate of [[Pan Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) for the federal constituency of [[Pokok Sena (federal constituency)|Pokok Sena]], Kedah in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 Malaysia general election]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=TheStarOnline|author=Shagar, Loshana K|title='Captain Marvel' Radhi Mat Din to take on Mahfuz|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/04/15/captain-marvel-radhi-mat-din-to-take-on-mahfuz/|date=15 April 2018|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> In the election, Radhi garnered 23401 votes and were defeated by the incumbent [[Mahfuz Omar]] from [[Parti Amanah Negara]] (AMANAH) of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) by majority of 5558 votes.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Berita Harian|language=Malay|author=Noorazura Abdul Rahman|title=Mahfuz pertahan Pokok Sena|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/politik/2018/05/423733/mahfuz-pertahan-pokok-sena|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P8 [[Pokok Sena (federal constituency)|Pokok Sena]], Kedah<ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"The Star GE14\">{{cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/|title=The Star Online GE14|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=24 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref>  \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/PAS}} |\n| rowspan=2|Muhamad Radhi Mat Din ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |23,401\n| rowspan=2|33.08% \n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} | \n|'''[[Mahfuz Omar]]''' ([[Parti Amanah Negara|'''AMANAH''']]) \n|align=\"right\"|\t'''28,959'''\n|'''40.93%'''\n| rowspan=2|71,910\n| rowspan=2|5,558\n| rowspan=2|82.76%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Said Ali Said Rastan ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |18,390\n|25.99%\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radhi Mat Din, Muhamad}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kedah]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian footballers]]\n[[Category:Malaysia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Kedah FA players]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games silver medalists for Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1989 Southeast Asian Games]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-footy-bio-stub}}\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2008}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Radhi Mat Din\n|image =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[Image:Radhi.jpg]] -->\n|fullname = Muhamad Radhi bin Mat Din\n|height =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1965|7|17}}\n|birth_place = [[Pokok Sena]], [[Kedah]], [[Malaysia]]\n|currentclub = [[Kedah FA]] (Assistant Coach)\n|clubnumber =\n|position = [[Midfielder]] \n|youthyears1=\n|youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1986\u20131992 | years2 =1986\u20132000\n| clubs1 = Kedah PKNK | clubs2 =[[Kedah FA]]\n| caps1 = ? | goals1 = ? | caps2 = ? | goals2 = ?\n|nationalyears1= 1989\u20131993\n|nationalteam1= [[Malaysia national football team|Malaysia]]\n|nationalcaps1= ? | nationalgoals1 = ?\n|pcupdate =\n|ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Muhamad Radhi bin Mat Din''' (born 17 July 1965) is a [[Malaysia]]n football coach, former [[Association football|footballer]], and politician.\n\n==Football career==\n\nHe spent his entire career by playing in midfield for [[Kedah FA]], where he was also the longest serving captain in club history starting from 1991 to 2000. Radhi made his debut in 1986 and cemented his place in the first team in the 1987 season, succeeding [[Lee Kin Hong]] as Kedah team captain in 1991.\n\nRadhi was an integral part in the golden era of the [[Darul Aman Stadium|Darul Aman]] based club during the 1980s and 1990s where Kedah reached the [[Malaysia Cup]] final matches for seven times from 1987 to 1993. He collected two Malaysia Cup winners medal in 1990 and 1993; [[Malaysia Super League|Division 1]] title in 1993; and [[Malaysia FA Cup|FA Cup]] in 1996. After Kedah won the League and FA Cup championship in 1993, Radhi was honoured with the Malaysian Best Player.\n\nRadhi had a good goal-scoring record, tackle, corner-kick taker and pass well. He represented [[Malaysia national football team|Malaysia]] for about four years from 1989 to 1993. Radhi also known by the nickname \"Captain Marvel\" among Kedah fans during his playing careers with his similar characters of former [[England|English]] footballer [[Bryan Robson]].\n\nAfter his playing career ended, he was employed by Kedah, serving as their second tactician behind [[Mohd Azraai Khor Abdullah]] alongside his former teammate and Kedah legendary [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Ahmad Sabri Ismail]] which three of them generated Kedah to clinched the double treble titles in 2006/07 and 2007/08 M.League seasons.\n\nRadhi played for the [[Malaysia national football team]] at the [[1989 Southeast Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|author=Courtney, Barrie|title=International Matches 1989 - Asisa|url=http://www.rsssf.com/intldetails/1989as.html|date=2 February 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\nOn 14 April 2018, Radhi was announced as a candidate of [[Pan Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) for the federal constituency of [[Pokok Sena (federal constituency)|Pokok Sena]], Kedah in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 Malaysia general election]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=TheStarOnline|author=Shagar, Loshana K|title='Captain Marvel' Radhi Mat Din to take on Mahfuz|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/04/15/captain-marvel-radhi-mat-din-to-take-on-mahfuz/|date=15 April 2018|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> In the election, Radhi garnered 23401 votes and were defeated by the incumbent [[Mahfuz Omar]] from [[Parti Amanah Negara]] (AMANAH) of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) by majority of 5558 votes.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Berita Harian|language=Malay|author=Noorazura Abdul Rahman|title=Mahfuz pertahan Pokok Sena|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/politik/2018/05/423733/mahfuz-pertahan-pokok-sena|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P8 [[Pokok Sena (federal constituency)|Pokok Sena]], Kedah<ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"The Star GE14\">{{cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/|title=The Star Online GE14|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=24 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref>  \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/PAS}} |\n| rowspan=2|Muhamad Radhi Mat Din ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |23,401\n| rowspan=2|33.08% \n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} | \n|'''[[Mahfuz Omar]]''' ([[Parti Amanah Negara|'''AMANAH''']]) \n|align=\"right\"|\t'''28,959'''\n|'''40.93%'''\n| rowspan=2|71,910\n| rowspan=2|5,558\n| rowspan=2|82.76%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Said Ali Said Rastan ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |18,390\n|25.99%\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radhi Mat Din, Muhamad}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kedah]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]