roup|isbn=978-1-57356-019-1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ethnicgroupsworl00levi}}\n<!--* Goran Burenhult, ''Traditional Peoples Today: Continuity and Change in the Modern World'' Illustrated History of Humankind, vol. 5 (1994).-->\n\n{{Ethnicity}}\n{{Indigenous peoples by continent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of ethnic groups}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups by region|*]]\n[[Category:Society-related lists|Ethnic groups]]\n[[Category:Lists of ethnic groups]]\n", "name_user": "Manabimasu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved dynamic  list", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_contemporary_ethnic_groups"}
{"title_page": "Pang Hok Liong", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Peng (surname)|Pang (\u5f6d)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[Malay styles and titles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Tuan]]\n| name = Pang Hok Liong\n| native_name =  {{nobold|\u5f6d\u5b66\u826f}}\n| native_name_lang = Chinese name\n| honorific-suffix   = {{small| [[Member of Parliament|MP]] }} \n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|7|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Labis]], [[Segamat District]], [[Johor]], [[Federation of Malaya]]\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| constituency_MP = [[Labis (federal constituency)|Labis]], [[Johor]]\n| parliament = Malaysian\n| term_start       = 10 May 2018\n| term_end         =\n| majority         =  3,408 (2018)\n| predecessor      = [[Chua Tee Yong]] ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor        = \n| constituency_AM2  = [[Bekok]], [[Johor]]\n| assembly2         = Johor State Legislative\n| term_start2       = 21 October 1990 \n| term_end2         = 24 April 1995\n| majority2         = 290 (1990)\n| predecessor2      = Tay Boon Chong ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor2        = Tan Kok Hong ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|Democratic Action Party]] (1988-)\n| occupation = [[Lawyer]]\n| profession = \n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| alma_mater=[[London University]]<br />[[Lincoln's Inn]]\n| website = {{facebook|Pang-Hok-Liong-\u5f6d\u5b66\u826f-2122081364745416}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Pang Hok Liong''' ({{zh|s=\u5f6d\u5b66\u826f|t=\u5f6d\u5b78\u826f|p=P\u00e9ng Xu\u00e9li\u00e1ng}}; born 22 July 1957)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://calon.ubah.my/?page=candidate_profile&state=JOHOR&code=P142|title=P142 Labis|publisher=[[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|Democratic Action Party]]|accessdate=17 February 2019|archive-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://archive.fo/pTdRv|url-status=live}}</ref> is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician. He is a member of the [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parlimen.gov.my/profile-ahli.html?uweb=dr&id=3666&lang=en|title=Profile at the official portal of Parliament of Malaysia|publisher=[[Parliament of Malaysia]]|accessdate=17 February 2019|archive-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://archive.fo/o0N7x|url-status=live}}</ref> He is the incumbent [[Parliament of Malaysia|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Labis (federal constituency)|Labis]] constituency since 2018. He was the [[Johor State Legislative Assembly]]man for [[Bekok]] for one term from 1990 to 1995 previously.\n\nPang previously contested for the [[Segamat (federal constituency)|Segamat]] seat in [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]] and [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]] general elections but had lost both the contests to [[Subramaniam Sathasivam]] of [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN). He did not participate in the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general elections]].\n\nIn the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]], Pang was elected to the [[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]] for the [[Labis (federal constituency)|Labis]] constituency, winning 16,977 of the 32,578 votes cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalgazette.agc.gov.my/outputp/pub_20180530_P.U.%20%28B%29%20318.pdf|title=Federal Government Gazette: Results of Contested Election and Statements of the Poll after the Official Addition of Votes \u2013 Parliamentary Constituencies for the State of Johore|date=28 May 2018|publisher=[[Attorney General of Malaysia|Attorney General's Chambers of Malaysia]]|accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref> He defeated the then [[Ministry of International Trade and Industry (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of International Trade and Industry]], [[Chua Tee Yong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/leaders-of-bns-ethnic-minority-parties-lose-parliamentary-seats|title=Leaders of BN's ethnic minority parties lose parliamentary seats|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=10 May 2018|author=Tan Hui Yee|url-status=live|accessdate=17 February 2019|archive-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217063015/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/leaders-of-bns-ethnic-minority-parties-lose-parliamentary-seats}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Johor State Legislative Assembly]]'''<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web  | title = Malaysia General Election   | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]  | url = http://undi.info/#  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref>\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[1990 Malaysian general election|1990]]\n|'''N8 [[Bekok]], P118 Labis'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|'''Pang Hok Liong''' ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n| align=\"right\" |'''7,638'''\n|'''49.27%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Lim Si Cheng ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |7,348\t\n|47.40%\n|15,502\t \n|290\n|70.43%\n|-\n|[[1995 Malaysian general election|1995]]\n|'''N8 [[Bekok]], P128 Labis'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|P