ron Highlands]], [[Pahang]]\n|rowspan=\"4\" {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|rowspan=\"4\"|{{nowrap|'''G Palanivel'''}} ([[Malaysian Indian Congress|'''MIC''']])\n|rowspan=\"4\" align=\"right\" |'''10,506'''\n|rowspan=\"4\"|'''48.03%'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} | \n|[[M. Manogaran|Manogaran Marimuthu]] ([[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|DAP]])\n|align=\"right\" |10,044\n|45.92%\n|rowspan=\"4\"|22,752\n|rowspan=\"4\"|462\n|rowspan=\"4\"|81.32%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Anti-Administration}} | \n|Mohd Shokri Mahmood ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Front|Berjasa]])\n|align=\"right\" | 912\n|4.17%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} | \n|Alagu Thangarajoo ([[Independent (politician)|IND]])\n|align=\"right\" | 308\n|1.41%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} | \n|Kisho Kumar Kathirveloo ([[Independent (politician)|IND]])\n|align=\"right\" | 101\n|0.46%\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20121223061822/http://gpalanivel.com.my:80/}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Samy Vellu]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Malaysian Indian Congress|Malaysian Indian Congress (MIC) President]]\n| years = 6 December 2010 \u2013 25 June 2014\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Subramaniam Sathasivam]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{First Najib cabinet}} \n{{Second Najib cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palanivel, G.}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Penang]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Hindus]]\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Indian Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Negara]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:University of Malaya alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Indian name|Palanivel|Govindasamy}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image =\n|imagesize =150px\n| honorific-prefix   = [[Malay styles and titles|Yang Berbahagia Datuk Seri]]\n| name = G Palanivel\n| honorific-suffix   = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Palanivel s/o K. Govindasamy\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|03|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Penang]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n| residence = Kuala Lumpur\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = 8th President of the [[Malaysian Indian Congress]] (MIC)\n| term_start = 6 December 2010\n| term_end = 25 June 2014\n| deputy = [[Subramaniam Sathasivam]]\n| predecessor = [[Samy Vellu]]\n| successor = [[Subramaniam Sathasivam]]\n\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment (Malaysia)|Malaysian Minister of Natural Resources and Environment]]\n| term_start2 = 16 May 2013\n| term_end2 = 29 July 2015\n| primeminister2 = [[Najib Razak]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Douglas Uggah Embas]]\n| successor2 = [[Wan Junaidi Tuanku Jaafar]]\n| constituency2 = Cameron Highlands\n\n| office3 = [[Prime Minister's Department|Malaysian Minister in the Prime Minister's Department]]<br /><small>Modernisation and Management, Public Administration, Public Complaints </small>\n| term_start3 = 9 August 2011\n| term_end3 = 5 May 2013\n| predecessor3 = ''Position established''\n| successor3 = [[Paul Low Seng Kuan]]\n\n| constituency_MP4  = [[Cameron Highlands (federal constituency)|Cameron Highlands]]\n| parliament4 = Malaysian\n| term_start4 = 5 May 2013\n| term_end4 = 10 May 2018\n| majority4 =\n| predecessor4 = [[Devamany S. Krishnasamy]]\n| successor4 = [[Sivarraajh Chandran]]\n\n| constituency_MP5  = [[Hulu Selangor]]\n| parliament5 = Malaysian\n| term_start5 = 21 October 1990\n| term_end5 = 8 March 2008\n| majority5 =\n| predecessor5 = [[Subramaniam Sinniah]]\n| successor5 = [[Zainal Abidin Ahmad (politician)|Zainal Abidin Ahmad]]\n\n| party =  [[Malaysian Indian Congress|MIC]] (until 2014) <br/>[[Independent politician|Independent]] (since 2014)\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| occupation = Politician\n| alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]] <br /> <small>Bachelor of Arts</small>\n| majority =\n| relations =\n| spouse = Kanagam Palanivel\n| children = 4 sons\n| website = {{URL|http://www.gpalanivel.com.my/}}\n| footnotes =\n|native_name= <small>{{nobold|\u0baa\u0bb4\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf}}</small>\n|native_name_lang=Tamil\n}}\n\n[[Malay styles and titles#Datuk Seri|Datuk Seri]] '''Palanivel s/o K. Govindasamy''' ({{lang-ta|\u0baa\u0bb4\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf|Pa\u1e3ba\u1e49iv\u0113l k\u014dvintac\u0101mi}}; born 1 March 1949), commonly known as '''G Palanivel''' is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician. He was the Minister of Natural Resources and Environment. He held his last positions in the Malaysian Government as the Minister in Prime Minister's Department and Deputy Minister of Plantation Industries and Commodities. His previously held the position as the Deputy Minister of Rural Development and Deputy Minister of Welfare and Family Development of Malaysia.  In the 8 March 2008 general elections, he was defeated in his bid for another five-year term as a member of parliament. He was appointed as Senator in May 2010 and became the Deputy Minister for the Ministry of Plantation Industries and Commodities. On 6 December 2010, he became the President of the [[Malaysian Indian Congress]] (MIC), which is a member of the ruling coalition [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN). On 30 July 2011, the Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] announced that Dato' G Palanivel to be appointed as Minister in the PM's Department on the MIC General Assembly and on 9 August 2011 Dato' G Palanivel took the oath of office to become the minister.\n\nAfter his victory in [[2013 Malaysian general election|13th General Election]], Palanivel was appointed as [[Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment (Malaysia)|Minister of Natural Resources and Environment]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mic.org.my/news-events/mic-news/2013/palanivel-ready-face-challenges-new-ministry|title=Palanivel Ready To Face Challenges at New Ministry|date=16 May 2013|work=[[Malaysian Indian Congress|MIC]]|accessdate=17 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nPalanivel was born in [[Penang]] on 1 March 1949. He obtained a Bachelor of Arts from [[University of Malaya]] in 1972, majoring in History. Initially he became a teacher at the Goon Institute in [[Kuala Lumpur]], and then at Maktab Adabi in [[Kuantan]]. In the same year as his graduation, he was elected Secretary of Petaling Branch of [[Malaysian Indian Congress]] (MIC), a political party which is part of the ruling coalition. He has been with the party since 1968.\n\nHe moved on to become a Research Assistant at the [[Muzium Negara]] (National Museum). In 1974, he went back to [[Penang]] to join the Consumer Association of Penang. There he rose to the position of Executive Director. His next career move was to join [[Bernama]] as a journalist in 1977. There he was elevated to become the Economic News Editor. It was during this period he was invited to become a Press Secretary to the Minister of Works who was (and is) also the President of MIC. That set the stage for the crucial take-off in his political career. He was chosen as a candidate in the country's general elections in 1990 and had won every single election as a member of parliament ever since until his loss in the 8 March 2008 elections when a tidal wave of voter sentiment against the ruling coalition came to the fore that resulted in the loss of four states out of thirteen to the opposition and in the loss of two-third majority in the Parliament.\n\nPositions in the Government commenced with Palanivel being appointed as the Parliamentary Secretary to the Ministry of National Unity. He rose further to become the Deputy Minister of Rural Development of [[Malaysia]] from 1999 until 2004 when he was made the Deputy Minister of Welfare and Family Development. He continued as the Deputy Minister until his defeat in the March 2008 general elections.\n\nPalanivel also had a stint in the corporate circle as a Business Adviser to Sports Toto and as Director of Telecoms Malaysia, Usha Martin and the Maharaja Network of [[Sri Lanka]].\n222\n\nPalanivel married Kanagam Palanivel and the couple has four sons.<ref name=biodata>{{cite news|title=PALANIVEL, DATUK |author= |work= SAIEE DRISS |url=http://biodatatokoh.blogspot.my/2008/03/palanivel-datuk.html |newspaper= |publisher= BIODATA TOKOH |language=Malay |date=2 March 2008|accessdate=7 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Political future ==\nIn June 2006, Palanivel, previously a Vice-President of [[Malaysian Indian Congress|MIC]], entered a new era of top level MIC leadership by defeating a 27-year incumbent, [[Malay titles|Dato']] [[S. Subramaniam|S Subramaniam]], to become the new Deputy President of MIC. He retained his position in the MIC Elections concluded on 12 September 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2009/9/12/nation/20090912091634&sec=nation |title=MIC polls: Samy Vellu's men sweep deputy, VP, most CWC posts|date=12 September 2009|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=12 September 2009}}</ref> Palanivel, was appointed MIC president to replace S Samy Vellu on 6 December 2010.\n\nPalanivel's position hitherto has been a Deputy Minister from 1999 until March 2008 when he failed to secure his parliamentary seat in the 2008 elections.\nFollowing the massive defeat of MIC representatives in the 2008 general elections, MIC's top leadership is conspicuously absent in the cabinet of the ruling coalition, [[Barisan Nasional]] that is made up of largely race based parties dominated by the Malay-based [[UMNO]]. It is the more junior members of MIC leadership who won in the General Elections who hold one ministerial and two deputy ministerial posts allocated for the party. Moreover, in the April 2009 new government line-up, MIC's representation had been reduced.\n\nAlthough the [[Barisan Nasional]] coalition won the 2008 general elections, it lost its previous eminent of position of securing parliamentary seats exceeding two-third majority. In the same elections, serious gains including capturing of 5 states out the total of 13 have been made by the alternative coalition, Pakatan Rakyat.\n\nOn 3 May 2010, G Palanivel was appointed as a Senator in the [[Dewan Negara|Parliament Upper House]].\n\nPalanivel returned to the federal cabinet portfolio and was appointed Deputy Minister of Plantation Industries and Commodities after a minor Cabinet reshuffle on 4 June 2010.\n\nOn 6 December 2010, G Palanivel was appointed as the 8th MIC President succeeding Samy Vellu who had held the post for 31 years.\n\nOn 5 May 2013, G Palanivel won the Cameron Highlands Parliament seat in the [[2013 Malaysian general election|13th Malaysian General Election]]. The Malaysian Indian Congress won 4 (Cameron Highlands, Segamat, Hulu Selangor, Tapah) Parliament seats in total and 5 (Gambir, Kahang, Tenggaroh, Gadek, Jeram Padang) State seats, an extra seat compared to the previous election in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/mic-survives-tough-battle-to-win-4-federal-seats/|title=MIC survives tough battle to win 4 federal seats|publisher=[[The Malaysian Insider]]|date=6 May 2013}}</ref> He was then appointed as Minister of Natural Resources and Environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2013/05/16/Palanivel-ready-to-face-challenges/ |title=Palanivel ready to face challenges |publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)]]|date=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2013, G Palanivel said that MIC was against the controversial bill which allows unilateral conversion of child below 18 years old into Islam.\n\nOn 5 July 2013, G Palanivel commented \"It was a fair move taking into consideration the sensitivities of various stakeholders and groups. MIC still stands by its statement that the consent of both parents are needed for the conversion of children to Islam,\" after the controversial bill on conversion of minors was withdrawn by the Malaysian ruling government Barisan Nasional.\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |access-date=28 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906083741/http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |archive-date=6 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum 13 Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri 2013|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref>  \n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[1990 Malaysian general election|1990]]\n|'''P084 [[Hulu Selangor]], [[Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''G Palanivel'''}} ([[Malaysian Indian Congress|'''MIC''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''20,839'''\n|'''63.74%'''\n|{{Party shading/S46}} | \n|Nazar Yakin ([[Semangat 46|S46]])\n|align=\"right\" |11,857\n|36.26%\n|34,306\n|8,982\n|73.10%\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[1995 Malaysian general election|1995]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|'''P088 [[Hulu Selangor]], [[Selangor]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{nowrap|'''G Palanivel'''}} ([[Malaysian Indian Congress|'''MIC''']])\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"right\" |'''20,546'''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|'''78.19%'''\n|{{Party shading/S46}} | \n|Adnan Din ([[Semangat 46|S46]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,594\n|17.48%\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 27,505\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 15,952\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 53.66%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} | \n|Peng Kim Sing ([[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|DAP]])\n|align=\"right\" | 1,137\n|4.33%\n|-\n|[[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''G Palanivel'''}} ([[Malaysian Indian Congress|'''MIC''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''22,143'''\n|'''61.65%'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} | \n|Halili Rahmat ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|align=\"right\" |13,548\n|37.72%\n|37,195\n|8,595\n|71.06%\n|-\n|[[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]]\n|rowspan=2|'''P094 [[Hulu Selangor]], [[Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''G Palanivel'''}} ([[Malaysian Indian Congress|'''MIC''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''27,807'''\n|'''67.52%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Ismail Kamus ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |13,324\n|32.35%\n|42,592\n|14,483\n|72.77%\n|-\n|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|G Palanivel}} ([[Malaysian Indian Congress|MIC]])\n|align=\"right\" |22,979\n|49.55%\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} | \n|'''Zainal Abidin Ahmad''' ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|'''PKR''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''23,177'''\n|'''49.97%'''\n|47,845\n|198\n|75.24%\n|-\n|rowspa