{"title_page": "Ramasamy Palanisamy", "text_new": "{{Short description|Incumbent Deputy Chief Minister II of Penang since March 2008}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[Malay titles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Professor|Prof.]] [[Doctor of Philosophy|Dr.]]\n| name               = Ramasamy Palanisamy <br/> <small>{{nobold|\u0b87\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf \u0baa\u0bb4\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf}}</small>\n| honorific-suffix   = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| image              = P Ramasamy DCM II of Penang.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| office             = Deputy Chief Minister 2 of Penang\n| term_start         = 13 March 2008\n| term_end           = \n| 1blankname         = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata          = [[Lim Guan Eng]] <br/> [[Chow Kon Yeow]]\n| alongside          = Mohd Firdaus Khairuddin (2008-2009), [[Mansor Othman]] (2009-2013), [[Mohd Rashid Hasnon]] (2013-2018), [[Ahmad Zakiyuddin Abdul Rahman]] (2018-)\n| predecessor        = Abdul Rashid Abdullah\n| successor          = \n| governor           = [[Abdul Rahman Abbas]]\n| constituency          = [[Perai (state constituency)|Perai]]\n|office1=[[Penang State Executive Council]]lor for State Economic Planning, Education, Human Resources, Science, Technology and Innovation\n| term_start1        = 13 March 2008\n| term_end1           = \n| governor1         = [[Abdul Rahman Abbas]]\n| 1blankname1         = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata1          = [[Lim Guan Eng]] <br/> [[Chow Kon Yeow]]\n| predecessor1       = Toh Kin Woon\n| successor1          = \n| constituency1         = [[Perai (state constituency)|Perai]]\n\n| constituency_MP2   = [[Batu Kawan]], Penang\n| parliament2        = Malaysian\n| term_start2        = 8 March 2008\n| term_end2          = 5 May 2013\n| predecessor2       = Huan Cheng Guan ([[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Gerakan]]\u2013[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor2         = [[Kasthuriraani Patto]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\u2013[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| majority2          = 9,485 (2008)\n\n| constituency_AM3   = [[Perai (state constituency)|Perai]]\n| assembly3          = Penang State\n| term_start3        = 8 March 2008\n| term_end3          =\n| predecessor3       = Rajapathy Kuppusamy ([[Malaysian Indian Congress|MIC]]\u2013[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor3         =\n| majority3          = 5,176 (2008) <br/> 7,159 (2013) <br/> 9,049 (2018)\n\n| office4            = \n| term_start4        =\n| term_end4          =\n| predecessor4       = \n| successor4         =\n| constituency4      =\n\n| birth_name         = P. Ramasamy s/o Palanisamy\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1949|5|10|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://calon.ubah.my/?page=candidate_profile&state=PULAU+PINANG&code=N16|title=Pakatan Harapan GE14 Candidate|website=calon.ubah.my}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Sitiawan]], [[Perak]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n| residence          = [[Penang]]\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| citizenship        = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party              = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) \n| otherparty         = [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| religion           = \n| occupation         = Politician \n| relations          =\n| spouse             = \n| children           =\n| alma_mater         = [[Indiana University]]<br/>[[McGill University]]<br/>[[University of Malaya]]\n| website            = {{url|http://www.pramasamy.com/}}\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n[[Professor|Prof.]] [[Doctor of Philosophy|Dr.]] '''P. Ramasamy s/o Palanisamy''' ({{lang-ta|\u0b87\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf \u0baa\u0bb4\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf}}; born 10 May 1949) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician who is currently the Deputy Chief Minister of the state of [[Penang]]. He is also the former [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of the Parliament]] of Malaysia for the [[Batu Kawan]] constituency (2008-2013), and currently represents the seat of [[Perai (state constituency)|Perai]] in the [[Penang State Legislative Assembly]] since 2008.  He is a member of the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) a component party in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition. His vocal opinions on [[Zakir Naik]] and support of [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu Nationalism]] policies in India during [[Narendra Modi]] regime had been controversial.\n\nRamasamy was elected to the Malaysian Parliament and Penang State Assembly in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 election]], defeating former [[Chief Minister of Penang|Penang Chief Minister]] [[Koh Tsu Koon]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Malaysia Decides 2008 | work = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] | url = http://thestar.com.my/election/  | accessdate = 20 December 2009}}</ref> He became Deputy Chief Minister of Penang after the election, serving under the new Chief Minister [[Lim Guan Eng]], making him the first person of Indian origin to hold the post of deputy chief minister in any Malaysian state.<ref name=\"from critic\">{{Cite news | last = Kuppusamy | first = Baradan | title = Dr P. Ramasamy \u2013 from critic to Penang No. 2 | newspaper = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] | date = 20 March 2008 | url = http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2008/3/20/nation/20685048&sec=nation | accessdate = 21 December 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604050048/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F3%2F20%2Fnation%2F20685048&sec=nation | archivedate = 4 June 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBefore entering politics, Ramasamy was a Professor at the [[Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia]] (UKM), from which he officially retired in May 2005. He later took up teaching positions in Germany and Singapore.<ref name =\"from critic\"/>\n\n==Education==\nRamasamy was born on May 10, 1949. His father Palaniyammal Palanichany and his mother worked in the fields of Malaya in 1920 and migrated from [[Tamil Nadu]]. He has six siblings. Ramasamy attended the Anglo-China Primary School in the late 1950s.\n\nHe earned his early education in [[Teluk Intan]], Perak, then obtained a First Degree in Journalism in New Zealand then continued his studies in Political Science at Indian University United States (1977) and at master's degree in McGill University, Canada (1980) then obtained a PhD at [[University of Malaya]] in 1991. He served as a lecturer from 1981 to 2005 at [[Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia]] (UKM) in Political Science.\n\n==Career==\nHe has served as the University of Singapore's Visiting Professor in Southeast Asian Political Education. From the beginning, he has been involved as an activist working on issues of labor beginning in the 1980s through INSAN (Institute of Social Analysis) Kuala Lumpur.\n\nHe has had 25 years of experience as a political science lecturer, who has served as a counselor and security consultant to several international peace efforts such as Acheh, Sri Lanka, the Philippines and Colombia. Ramasamy served as an advisor to the Global Labor University [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO) 2004.\n\n==Political career==\nRamasamy is active as an activist who fights for the fate of minorities in Sri Lanka and Acheh Merdeka. The two parties involved in Acheh finally agreed to sign a peace agreement on August 5, 2005. On 26 August 2005 he was fired from [[Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia|UKM]] for no reason. Afterwards he taught in Germany and Singapore and began to engage in [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]] activities.\n\nStarted joining DAP officially in September 2005. Writing several books and many articles in local and international journals. He defeated former [[Chief Minister of Penang]] Tan Sri [[Koh Tsu Koon]] for the [[Batu Kawan (federal constituency)|Batu Kawan]] parliamentary constituency in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general election]]. He is also Penang State Assemblyman N16 [[Perai (state constituency)|Perai]]. In 2008, the [[Barisan Nasional|BN]] government fell to [[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]] as DAP had won 19 seats, [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]] 9 seats and [[Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]] only 1 seat. He was appointed Deputy Chief Minister II of Penang and was the first Indian to be elected to the post.\n\nIn the exco of the Penang government, he is responsible for state economic planning, education and human resources, science, technology and innovation.\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Zakir Naik ===\nOn 10 April 2016, P Ramasamy, called prominent Islamic preacher [[Zakir Naik|Dr. Zakir Naik]] as \"[[satan]]\", he wrote in his Facebook post \u201cLet us get \u2018satan\u2019 Zakir Naik out of this country!\u201d. After severe backlash he removed his posting, apologized and said sorry for causing uneasiness and unhappiness among Muslims in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2016/04/12/ramasamy-apologises-for-calling-dr-zakir-naik-satan/|title=Ramasamy apologises for calling Dr Zakir Naik 'satan'|last=Reporters|first=F. M. T.|date=2016-04-12|website=Free Malaysia Today|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n\n=== India's [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu Nationalism]] policies under [[Narendra Modi]] ===\nDuring October 2019, on the event of military lock-down of Kashmir (region known for military excesses), P Ramasamy criticized<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaysiantimes.com.my/what-has-mahathir-got-against-india/|title=What has Mahathir got against India?|last=Palanisamy|first=Ramasamy|date=October 23, 2019|work=The Malaysian Times|access-date=October 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Mahathir's call for UN to restore human rights in Kashmir.\n\nDuring December 2019, despite global condemnation by countries and human right organizations on India's citizenship amendment act, detention camp deaths and killing in protests; P Ramasamy had series of articles<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/opinion/2019/12/21/dr-m-may-have-misunderstood-new-indian-citizenship-law/|title=Dr M may have misunderstood new Indian citizenship law|last=Palanisamy|first=Ramasamy|date=December 21, 2019|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/505028|title=Dr M backs secular principles only when Muslims are minorities|last=Palanisamy|first=Ramasamy|date=December 27, 2019|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=December 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and TV appearances criticizing Mahathir for commenting on India's citizenship amendment and the deaths caused (due to protests and in detention camp deaths for lack of documents).\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |accessdate=27 May 2010}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | author2 =\n  | title = Malaysia General Election\n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data | publisher =  Malaysiakini\n  | date =\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = 5 May 2014}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref>\n!Year\n!Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|'''P46 [[Batu Kawan (federal constituency)|Batu Kawan]], [[Penang]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''P. Ramasamy'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''23,067'''\n|'''62.94%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan